Macedonians vote to change country's name
Macedonians voted in a referendum on Sunday to change the country's name to the "Republic of Northern Macedonia", a name change that would resolve a decades-long dispute with Greece that has blocked the country's aspirations for membership of the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, considers the name of its northern neighbour to be a territorial claim for its territory and has therefore opposed its accession to the EU and NATO.
In June, the governments of the two countries signed an agreement on a new name proposal, but nationalist opponents felt that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of the Slavic majority of Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov has announced that he will not vote in the referendum, and the campaign against the vote raises doubts as to whether the turnout will reach the required 50% for the result to be legal.
The question on the ballot was: 'Are you on the side of NATO and EU membership, accepting the agreement with Greece'.
Proponents of the name change, such as Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that the price is worth paying so that Macedonia, which has emerged from the collapse of Yugoslavia, can seek membership of both the EU and NATO.
"I came today to vote for the future of our country, for the youth of Macedonia so that they can live in freedom as members of the European Union, because it means a safer life for all of us," said 79-year-old Olivera Georgijevska in Skopje.
Although the vote is not legally binding, enough Members have said that they respect the outcome of the vote to have a decisive impact.
A change of name requires a two-thirds majority in Parliament.
According to the Central Electoral Commission, no irregularities had been reported by 1 p.m.
However, the turnout was only 16, compared to 34 per cent of the previous 2016 parliamentary elections, when 66% of eligible voters finally cast their votes.
"I came to vote for my children and for our place in Europe," said 62-year-old Gjose Tanevsky, who voted in the capital city of Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko voted in a referendum on Macedonia's name change in Strumica, Macedonia, on 30 September 2018. The name change would open the way to NATO and EU membership .
54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov prepared a small stage and placed chairs in front of the tents erected by those boycotting the referendum in front of the Skopje Parliament.
"We support NATO and the EU, but we want to join with our heads up and not through the kitchen door," Kavadarkov said.
"We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they don’t want to take us as Macedonia, we can turn elsewhere, like China and Russia, as part of Euro-related integration.”
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership will bring much-needed investment to Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of more than 20%.
"I believe a large majority will vote for the name change because more than 80% of our citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO," said Zaev after voting.
He said the "yes" vote was "our future."
An opinion poll published by the Political Research Institute of Macedonia on Monday referred to a voter turnout of 30-43% in the referendum - that is, below the required activity.
In a second survey conducted by Macedonian Telma TV, 57% of respondents planned to vote on Sunday.
Seventy percent of them said they would vote yes.
For a referendum to be successful, the voter turnout must exceed 50% by a single vote.
The failure of the referendum would be the first serious setback to the pro-Western government since it came to power in May last year.
