Harvard students take an instructional course on adequate rest
This year, all undergraduate students at Harvard University will take a course designed to increase student rest. The course is a counter-strike to the university’s thriving macho culture, where students weigh long nights with the power of caffeine.
According to the researcher, the students of the best university in the world are often quite ignorant of the basics of their own well-being.
Charles Czeisler, a professor at Harvard University School of Medicine who works on sleep research at Brigham and Women's Hospital, believes the course will be the first of its kind in the United States.
Czeisler got the idea for the course after lecturing on the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
"After the lecture, a young woman came to me and said, 'Why am I only hearing about it now, my last year of college?'
No one had ever told her about the need for sleep, which I found surprising," she told the Telegraph in an interview.
The course, organized for the first time this year, guides students on how proper sleep habits support academic and athletic performance and improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor at Harvard University School of Medicine and vice president of health services at the university, says the university ended up organizing a course after hearing how students suffered from severe sleep deficits during the week of study.
The one-hour course includes a set of interactive tasks.
In one section, students are presented with a picture of a dorm room where the student can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports equipment and books, thus getting information about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the effect of sleep deprivation on sports performance and the importance of regular evening activities.
In the second section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routines.
"We know that this does not have an immediate impact on students' behavior.
We believe, however, that they have the right to know about these issues in exactly the same way as they have the right to know about the health effects of smoking," adds Professor Czeisler.
According to Professor Czeisler, all-night study marathons are still a subject of pride, and modern technology and the ever-increasing pressures of students made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
"Having adequate and high-quality sleep should be a 'secret weapon' for students against stress, fatigue and anxiety, and even weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes a state similar to starvation in the brain, which is why people are constantly hungry," the professor points out.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student in chemical and physical psychology, helped Professor Czeisler plan the course after attending one of his courses in his first year at Harvard last year.
He says that the course opened his eyes and gave the impetus to a comprehensive course for all students on campus.
He hopes that all postgraduate students can complete a similar course of study before moving to a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students set an alarm clock to also remind them of bedtime time in addition to waking up in the morning, and urges them to keep in mind the side effects of electronic display devices and LED lighting on the "blue light" on the circadian rhythm, which can make it difficult to fall asleep.
