Next, a page from our "Sunday Morning" almanac: September 30, 1882. Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger, the future physicist, was born in Germany today 136 years ago.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity. The invention later led to the development of a device known as a geiger meter.
The method became one of the pillars of science, and also a central concept of pop culture. For example, the 1950 film "Coronado Clocks", in which Roy Rogers and Dale Evans play scientists who seem quite like cowboys, fits well:
Man: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: "It's a geiger meter. It's used to search for radioactive minerals like uranium.
When you put the headphones in your ears, you can actually hear the effect of radioactive radiation on the minerals."
Evans: "Look, it's really driving!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945 a few days before his 63rd birthday.
However, the invention that bears his name still lives on.
New cancer vaccine able to teach immune system to ‘see’ malignant cells
A new cancer vaccine is able to teach the immune system to ‘see’ malignant cells and destroy them
Vaccine teaches immune system to identify malignant cells as part of treatment
The method involves the isolation of resistant cells from the patient and their modification in the laboratory
After treatment, cells injected back into the body are able to ‘see’ the proteins typical of many cancers
The experimental vaccine has produced promising results in different cancer patients.
For example, a patient with ovarian cancer lost their cancer cells within 18 months after being treated with a vaccine that teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells.
The method isolates resistant cells from the patient and modifies them in the laboratory so that they are able to ‘see’ the HER2 proteins typical of many cancers. The modified cells are then injected back into the body.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, U.S.A., describes the method: "Based on our results, this is a very promising vaccine."
HER2 "controls the growth of several types of cancer," explains Professor Berzofsky. "These include breast cancer and ovarian, lung and colon cancers."
A similar approach —taking resistant cells from a patient and teaching them to attack cancer cells —has also produced results in the treatment of one type of leukaemia.
