Some viewers were not exactly happy after staying up all night because of the match.
One MMA friend opened on Twitter, describing the replacement of the match with a children's cartoon as "some kind of sick joke".
"According to the law, the content in question was not suitable to be presented at six o'clock in the morning, so they had to switch it to a children's program," explained Dave Schwartz, Bellator's senior vice president of marketing and communications for changing the program".
"Pipsa Pig, yes".
Bellator CEO Scott Coker said that schedules will be worked on so that UK viewers can follow events in the future.
"I'm thinking of a rebroadcast that will probably make the show work," Coker said.
"However, it's six o'clock in the morning and we can't get the show out until Sunday for our time, which is Monday for their time.
We're working on it.
You can believe that as the program changed in their heads, messages began to flow one way or the other and not all of them were friendly.
We tried to correct the error because we thought it was a technical problem.
However, this was not the case; it was a legislative matter.
I can promise you that this will not happen next time.
We limit the number of matches to five instead of six, as usual, trying to offer our fans more and trying too hard.
This is a sad situation.”
Desert Island Discs: Tom Daley felt inferior because of his sexuality
Swimming jumper and Olympic athlete Tom Daley says he felt inferior to everyone else because of his sexuality, but this motivates him to succeed.
A 24-year-old athlete says she didn’t realize until she came to high school that “not everyone is the same as me.”
Daley, speaking on Radio 4's Desert Island Discs, hosted by Lauren Laverne, said she talked about gay rights to give 'hope' to others.
He also explains how winning after having a child at the Olympics was no longer so important.
Kristy Young, a permanent host of the long-running radio show, has taken several months off due to illness.
While appearing as a guest on Laverne's first show, Daley said she felt "less" than everyone else when she was young because "it was not socially acceptable to like boys and jobs".
“To this day, feeling less and different has been a reality, and they have given me the strength and energy I’ve needed to succeed.”
She says she wanted to show that she was ‘something’ so that she wouldn’t disappoint everyone when her sexuality was finally revealed.
A two-time Olympic bronze medalist has become a high-profile LGBT activist, and he will appear at this year's Commonwealth Games to plead for the criminalization of homosexuality in other countries.
He said he came out because he felt lucky to be able to live openly without consequences, and wanted to give ‘hope’ to other people.
The three-time world champion recounts his fall in love with a man — American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013 — "became a surprise".
Daley married this 20-year-old Oscar winner last year, but says the age gap has never been a problem.
"If you experience so many things at such a young age" — he attended his first Olympics at the age of 14, and his father died of cancer three years later — "it's hard to find another person of his age who would have experienced similar fort and adversity," Daley says.
The couple had a son in June — Robert Ray Black-Daley — as a result of which Daley's "whole perspective" has changed.
"If you had asked me last year, my life would have revolved around winning a gold medal," he says.
"You know, there are bigger things than a gold Olympic medal.
Robbie is my Olympic gold medal."
His son was named after Daley's father, who died in 2011 at the age of just 40 from brain cancer.
Daley said that his father never accepted that he would die, and one of the last things he asked Daley was about the tickets to the 2012 Olympic Games, he wanted to sit in the front row.
"I couldn't tell him he's not going to be there anymore to be in the front row," Daley says.
"I held his hand when his breath stopped. It was only after his breathing had really stopped and he was dead that I finally realized that he was not invulnerable," he says.
The following year, Daley competed at the 2012 Olympics and won bronze.
“I knew this was something I’ve dreamed of all my life — jumping in front of a home audience at the Olympics. There’s no better feeling,” Daley says.
This was also an inspiration for his first song selection on the air — Heather Small's song "Proud" — which evoked feelings already as he was preparing for the Olympics, and which still gets his skin on chicken meat.
Desert Island Discs is broadcast on BBC Radio 4 on Sundays at 11:15 BST.
Mickelson at Saturday's Ryder Cup
