Mickelson, who plays in a two-yearly event for the record 12th time, went on the bench by Captain Jim Furyk for the fourball and foursome to be played on Saturday.
Usually the center of attention, the American five-time Major tournament winner now spent half a day as a cheerleader and the other half on the field trying to gain control of his bat.
The 48-year-old Mickelson, not even considered to be one of the most accurate drivers of his career, is not the ideal choice for a tight Le Golf National course where a long-grown roughy punishes inaccurate punches.
If Mickelson doesn't have enough resistance in the field himself, the ninth game on Sunday will be played by well-known British Open winner Francesco Molinari, who will play alongside newcomer Tommy Fleetwood, who aims to show up on a streak of all four wins this week.
If Americans who are four points behind in 12 doubles get a flying start, Michelson's game could prove to be extremely important.
Furyk has expressed his confidence in his player, but what else could be said in the situation.
"He perfectly understands the role he played today. He patted me on the back, squeezed me and said he was ready for tomorrow," Furyk said.
“He has a lot of self-confidence.
He’s arguably one of the best players and has brought so much to his team in the past, and this week.
