European team captain Thomas Bjorn knows how long the lead can quickly disappear
Thomas Bjorn, captain of the European team, knows from experience that Ryder Cup's extensive lead before the final day doubles can become a bumpy journey.
The Danish player made his debut in 1997 at Valderrama, where the side led by the Seve Ballesteros had a five-point lead over the Americans, but who made it to the winner on the limestones by just barely the measure of his nose and won by the narrowest margin of 141⁄2 to 131⁄2.
"It reminds itself of how we led briskly at Valderrama, we led briskly at Brookline, where we lost, but won at Valderrama, albeit scarcely," said Bjorn after watching the 2018 team's 5-1 wins both Friday and yesterday, taking a 10-1 lead at Le Golf National.
