Thomas has been given the task of trying to lead a defensive battle and faces Rory McIlroy in the most important game. Paul Casey, Justin Rose, Jon Rahm, Tommy Fleetwood and Ian Poulter are next in order to face their European opponents.
"I put the guys of the group in this order because I think it carries the whole tournament through," Bjorn commented on his doubles choices.
Germany's new warship delayed again
The German fleet's newest frigate should have been put into service in 2014. The purpose of the vessel is to replace obsolete Cold War equipment, but it will be deployed at the earliest next year due to faulty systems and explosively increasing costs, local media reports.
According to a military spokesperson for Die Zeit, the first ship of the new Baden-Württemberg frigate class ‘Rheinland-Pfalz’ has been postponed until the first half of 2019.
The ship was scheduled to join the fleet in 2014, but worrying post-delivery problems have haunted an ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg-class ships ordered by the Navy in 2007 are intended to replace the aging Bremen-class frigates.
According to available data, they are equipped with powerful cannons, missile systems to combat aircraft and surface vessels, and stealth technology such as radar reflectivity, infrared and acoustic signal perceptibility.
One of the most important features of the ship is its longer maintenance interval - new frigates should be able to operate at sea for up to two years without ever visiting the home port.
However, the constant delays mean that the state-of-the-art warships, which are said to be designed to enhance Germany’s influence in the overseas territories, are already obsolete by the time they enter service, notes Die Zeit.
The ill-fated F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to commission the ship and returned it to Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This is the first time the Navy has returned the ship since its delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but there has been talk in the German media about essential "software and equipment failures" that make a warship unfit for combat missions.
Software deficiencies are particularly important because the crew size of Baden-Württemberg-class ships is around 120, which is only half the crew of older Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, it turned out that the ship is significantly overweight, reducing its performance and limiting the fleet's possibilities for subsequent upgrades.
Rheinland-Pfalz, with a capacity of 7,000 tons, is believed to be twice as heavy as the equivalent class ships used by Germany in World War II.
In addition to defective equipment, the price tag for the entire project is also becoming a problem.
The price is reported to have risen to a stunning sum of EUR 3.1 billion, compared to the original price of EUR 2.2 billion.
Problems with the introduction of new frigates have emerged as German naval power has recently been warned of shrinking.
Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German Parliament's defence committee, pointed out earlier this year that the fleet's usable vessels are "running out".
According to the authority, the problem has grown over time because old vessels have been decommissioned but no new ones have been delivered to replace them.
He complained that no Baden-Württemberg-class frigates could have been deployed by the Navy.
Environmental Organization Eavesdrops on the Hidden Lives of Bats
A new study in an area in the Scottish Highlands seeks to find out how bats use the terrain to hunt for food.
The new study is hoped to bring new light to the behavior of these unique flying mammals and to guide in future conservation measures.
A study conducted by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will monitor bats, as well as earbugs and hydroponics in the Inverewe Garden area of the Botanical Garden in Wester Ross.
In the study, special recording devices are placed at important points in the area to monitor the activity of bats during the season.
The organisation’s employees and volunteers also carry out mobile measurements using portable observation equipment.
The frequencies of the sounds and the species in question are verified by expert analysis.
Based on the results, a habitat map and a report are created in which the behaviour of bats can be presented in a picture that follows the scale of the area.
Rob Dewar, the organization's conservation adviser, hopes the results reveal which habitat areas are most important to bats, and how different species exploit them.
The information helps in the planning of habitat areas, such as the creation of meadows and the management of forest areas, so that bats and related species are taken into account.
The populations of bats in Scotland and throughout Great Britain have declined considerably over the past 100 years.
Construction and earthworks threaten bats' resting places and habitats.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as can flypapers and certain chemicals used in building materials, as well as attacks by pets.
Bats are not actually blind.
However, due to nocturnal hunting practices, their ears are more useful for catching prey than their eyes.
Bats use advanced echo positioning technology to detect insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The National Trust for Scotland is an organization dedicated to protecting the rural environment that maintains more than 270 historic buildings, 38 notable gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country — and they take bats seriously.
It employs ten experts who regularly carry out surveys, inspections of resting places and, in some cases, animal rescue operations.
The organization has even established Scotland's first and only protected area dedicated to bat protection on the land of the Threave Manor in the Dumfries and Galloway area, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten species of bats.
David Thompson says the area is ideal for bats.
"Threave is very suitable for bats," he says.
"We have old buildings and trees and, overall, a good living environment.
Not everything is known about bats yet, so our work here and in other areas of the organization helps us to better understand what bats need to succeed."
He stresses the importance of inspecting buildings for bats before refurbishment, since the destruction of one bat resting place can unintentionally cause the deaths of up to 400 female bats and chicks and destroy an entire local population.
Bats are protected animals and are prohibited from killing, disturbing or destroying their resting places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official of the bat conservation organization, encourages the public to participate in conservation work.
He says, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and we don't yet know how their populations are doing."
