Brexit: UK 'will regret' car production
The UK would "repent forever" if it lost its position as the world's leading car manufacturer after Brexit, Trade Minister Greg Clark said.
He added that he was "concerned" with the announcement by Toyota's UK unit to temporarily suspend production in Burnaston at its factory near Derby if Britain leaves the EU without a deal.
"We need a deal," Clark says.
Japanese automaker says the impact of border delays will be visible as job losses if Brexit ends without a deal.
The plant in Burnaston, where Toyota's Auris and Avensis models are produced, produced nearly 150,000 cars last year, 90% of which were exported to the rest of the European Union.
“My view is that if the UK leaves the EU suddenly at the end of March, there will be interruptions in production at our factory,” said Marvin Cooke, CEO of Burnaston, Toyota.
Other UK-based car manufacturers, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover, have expressed fears about exiting the European Union as to how cross-border trade will work.
BMW, for example, has announced that it will close its Mini factory for a month after Brexit.
The main concern concerns supply chain risks, according to car manufacturers, in the event of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota's production line is run on a timely JOT principle, where parts arrive at the factory every 37 minutes from their suppliers in the UK and the EU, and cars are manufactured on request.
If the UK leaves the EU without an agreement on 29 March, it could cause disruption at the border, which, according to the industry, could lead to delays and shortages of parts.
A 24-hour warehouse at the Derbyshire plant will be impossible to maintain and production will be halted.
Clark says Theresa May's EU relations plan is "precisely calibrated to avoid these checks at the border".
"We need a deal. We want the best deal that not only means success in the current situation, but it is an opportunity that we need to take advantage of," he said on BBC Radio 4's Today programme.
"Not only the statements of Toyota, but also those of other manufacturers, show that we absolutely need to be able to continue the very well-functioning series of supply chains to date."
Toyota does not know how long production will be stopped, but warns that the additional costs would reduce the plant's competitiveness and ultimately result in job losses.
Peter Tsouvallaris, who has worked in Burnaston for 24 years and is a trade union official at the factory, says concern is growing among members: "In my experience, lost jobs will never return.
A government spokesperson says, "We need to present a precise and credible plan for our future relations with the EU."
Trump's meeting with Rosenstein could be delayed again, White House says
Donald Trump's challenging meeting with Assistant Attorney General Rod Rosenstein could "have to postpone another week" around Supreme Court Justice nominee Brett Kavanaugh due to a rowdy controversy, the White House announced Sunday.
Rosenstein oversees the work of Special Counsel Robert Mueller, who in turn investigates Russia's interference in the elections, Trump's assistants' links with Russia, and any actions the president may take to obstruct justice.
For months, there have been rumours in Washington that Trump was going to fire the Assistant Attorney General, which would compromise the impartiality of Mueller's investigation.
Earlier this month, the New York Times reported that Rosenstein discussed the possibility of secretly recording conversations with Trump, as well as the possibility of firing the president on the basis of the 25th Amendment to the United States Constitution.
Rosenstein has denied the report.
Rosenstein visited the White House last Monday, and the purpose of the meeting has been reported to be Rosenstein's resignation from office.
However, President Trump was on a visit to the United Nations in New York at the time, so the date of the meeting was announced Thursday.
Trump said he would "not prefer" to fire Rosenstein, but the meeting was postponed because its date coincided with the Senate Judiciary Committee hearing in which Kavanaugh and one of the women who accused him, Dr Christine Blasey Ford, were both witnesses.
On Friday, Trump ordered a week-long FBI investigation into allegations against Kavanaugh, which further postponed the Senate plenary vote.
Trump's press secretary Sarah Sanders appeared on Fox News' Sunday program.
When asked about Rosenstein's meeting, Sanders said, "There is no set date for this. It could be next week, this week, it could be postponed for another week due to everything else that is going on in the Supreme Court at the moment.
It remains to be seen, but I always want to keep the press informed."
Some reporters might disagree with this claim: Sanders has not held a White House press conference since September 10.
Chris Wallace asked why.
Sanders says the reason for the lack of press conferences is due to reasons other than distaste for the "attention-seeking" of TV reporters, but noted, however, "I do not deny the fact that they are attention-seeking."
Sanders, however, suggested that direct contacts between Trump and the press would increase.
"The president holds more questioning hours than any president before him," he says, and yet more evidence to quote: "We've checked those numbers."
"Press conferences will still be held," Sanders said, "but it will be infinitely better if the media have the opportunity to ask questions directly to the President of the United States than to talk to me.
