Foreign buyers will be subject to a higher stamp tax when buying real estate in the UK
Foreign buyers will be subject to a higher stamp tax when buying real estate in the UK. The extra money will be used to help the homeless, according to the Conservative Party's new plans.
The amendment aims to neutralize Corby's success in attracting young voters
An increase in the stamp tax applies to those who do not pay taxes in the United Kingdom
The Ministry of Finance expects to raise up to £120 million a year to help the homeless
Theresa May will announce today a higher stamp tax rate from foreign buyers when they buy real estate in the UK. The extra money will be used to help the homeless.
The measure will be seen as an attempt to neutralize Jeremy Corby's efforts to attract young voters. Corby has made promises of cheaper housing and paid attention to the taxation of high incomes.
An increase in the stamp tax will target people and businesses who do not pay taxes to the UK, and the extra money from this will be directed to government action to ease the plight of the homeless.
The additional fee — which is added to the current stamp tax in addition to the second and investment housing increases added two years ago — can be up to 3%.
The finance minister expects the increase to generate up to £120 million annually.
An estimated 13 per cent of London's new buildings are purchased by non-residents in the UK, raising prices and making it difficult for first-time home buyers to enter the home-ownership market.
Many wealthy areas in the UK — especially its capital — have become ‘ghost cities’ because many foreign property owners spend most of their time abroad.
The new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson proposed lowering the stamp tax as a way to make it easier for young people to buy first-time homes.
He accused the big construction companies of keeping real estate prices high by buying land and not building it, and urged Prime Minister May to abandon quotas for affordable housing to remedy Britain's "disgraceful situation of housing".
Corbyn has published a striking series of proposals to reform the housing market, including restrictions on rents and an end to "productive evictions".
He would also like to give the councils more power in matters related to the construction of new housing.
Prime Minister May says, "I said last year that I was going to dedicate the British dream of my prime minister — that every generation's life should be better than its predecessors — to restoring.
This means repairing our broken housing market.
Britain will always be open to people who want to live, work and build their lives here.
However, it cannot be right that people who do not live in the UK, as well as companies located abroad, can buy housing as easily as hard-working British residents.
For too many people, owning a home has become far too distant a dream, and the shame of homelessness remains a fact."
Jack Ross: 'My ultimate goal is to lead the Scottish national team'
