Perfect time to enjoy a pint is Saturday at 5:30 p.m., study shows
The heat wave of the summer has given a boost to pubs struggling with Britain’s difficulties, but at the same time has put more pressure on restaurant chains.
According to statistics, the sales of pub and bar chains grew by 2.7% during July, but the revenue of restaurants decreased by 4.8%.
Peter Martin, a business consultant at CGA, who compiled the figures, says: "Continuous sunny weather and England's longer-than-expected participation in the World Cup meant that July became like June with pub sales 2.8% higher, while the month was worse for restaurants.
The 1.8% decrease in restaurant sales in June only worsened in July.
Pubs and bars focused on the drinking side were the most successful. Their like-for-like sales grew more than the decline in restaurant sales.
Food-focused pubs also suffer from heat, but less dramatically than those running restaurants.
It seems that people just wanted to go out with drinking in mind.
Sales of pubs and bars run by companies increased by 6.6% over the month, with food sales falling by 3%."
Paul Newman of RSM, a leisure and hotel restaurant consulting firm, says: “The results continue a trend that has continued since the end of April.
